{
  "text": "In this research, all slow growing rhizobia from R. monosperma are resistant to 2% NaCl and sensitive to 3% NaCl (Table 4 ). In contrast, the strains B. retamae isolated from R. sphaerocarpa and R. monosperma obtained from Morocco and Spain did not grow in presence of 1% NaCl [CITATION_1] . The relatively high tolerance to NaCl reported for two isolates RH 18 and RH 29 identified by [CITATION_2] as Sinorhizobium were able to tolerate a high NaCl concentration from 1 to 3%. Moreover, [CITATION_3] recorded that isolates from R. sphaerocarpa RST-1 and RS-3 were able to grow at 0.1% NaCl, whilst RST-2 showed resistance at a high NaCl concentration equal to 2.5 to 3%. It is often believed that saline soils naturally select strains more tolerant to salinity. Besides, the ability of bacteria to grow well in high salt concentration has been shown to be dependent on the accumulation of internal solutes that maintain the osmotic balance of the cells and thus counteract the outflow of water molecules [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] , likewise many rhizobia respond to salt stress by increasing the intracellular concentration of K + and glutamate [CITATION_6] .",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "25362271",
